data.content:
Yes! MSTest v3.8+ supports **typed tuples** with `DynamicData`, eliminating the `object[]` boxing and giving you compile-time type safety:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

For simple constant values like these, `[DataRow]` is even more concise:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

**Trade-offs:**
- **`[DataRow]`** — simplest, but limited to compile-time constants (no objects, arrays, etc.)
- **Typed `DynamicData`** — type-safe, supports complex types, catches mismatches at compile time instead of runtime
